<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=7726&amp;p=33252#p33252"><![CDATA[
Finally, success!<br /><br />When I got you last email/reply, I checked whether the Classic Shell executable was being run as &quot;Administrator.&quot; While it didn't appear to me to be in that state, I decided to, once again, run your utility to completely remove Classic Shell, and all of the associated files. Additionally, I ran several Registry checkers, including CCleaner. It found more stuff, and I got rid of that too.<br /><br />Then I rebooted, again, and re-installed Classic Shell in the non-Adminstrator (so named) user; note, however, that this other user is also marked as being an administrator, just not &quot;THE&quot; Administrator.<br /><br />As usual, the installation went fine, and indeed, the Classic Shell configuration came up when I clicked on the Start button. Once set, the Start button opens Classic Shell each time! <br /><br />Next, I rebooted, and logged in as &quot;The&quot; Administrator user, and again, Classic Shell opened without difficulty!<br /><br />I don't know what happened originally, but it is all working now.<br /><br />Thanks for your guidance - and that special Utility!<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=21550">ENAR</a> — Mon Jul 10, 2017 7:24 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
